1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 O-O 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 b5 $1 {We look at
White's king side development! Have a little laugh and ask our opponent
whether he is brave enough to open the position?} 7. cxb5 c6 8. bxc6 $6 {I
think taking the pawn is not such a good idea. It basically leads to a
position where all the initiative is with Black. White is a pawn up but will
have to play very accurately to reach a position where he can take advantage
of the extra pawn.} Nxc6 9. Nf3 $6 {I don't like this move. This gives Black
an opportunity to post the bishop on a6. As a result, whenever White plays e3,
he will lose the chance of 0-0.} Ba6 $1 {Developing the piece to an active
square and freeing the c8 square for the rook.} 10. e3 Ne4 $1 {The knight on
e4 is a good piece to have. Black already possesses a huge initiative.} 11. Qc2
Bxf1 12. Kxf1 f5 {In this way, Black anchors his knight on the central square.
Later maybe, he can use the f6 square for a rook lift from f8; and now the
idea is also to infiltrate via the 'c' file, whereas White is quite passive
and has really not many active plans.} 13. h4 $6 {White wants to exchange the
knights from g5.} Qa5 {Clearing the way for the rook to come to c8, if it
would like to; also the queen stands quite well on this square.} 14. Ng5 Nb4 (
14... Rac8 {Would have been better.} 15. Nxe4 fxe4 16. Qxe4 $2 Qb5+ 17. Kg1 Na5
$19 {With the knight coming to b3, queen coming to e2 and both rooks on open
files, Black's position is a picture of complete domination.}) 15. Qe2 Nd5 {
The two knights have taken up central posts on light squares. You will realise
that in this opening Black is usually following a light-squared strategy, i.e.
to put all his pieces on light squares, as the light squares are so weak.} 16.
Nxe4 fxe4 {The d5 knight is far far superior to the c1 bishop.} 17. Bd2 Qb6 (
17... Qa4 {Was a better square, playing on the light squares.}) 18. b4 Rac8 19.
Rh3 Rc2 20. Rg3 $2 (20. Kg1 Nc3 21. Qe1 $11) 20... Nc3 $1 {The game is now
over, as the queen has no good square to go to.} 21. Qc4 (21. Qg4 Qb5+ 22. Ke1
g6 $19 {White's king can do nothing against the various threats he faces.} 23.
h5 (23. Bxc3 Rfxf2 $19) 23... Rf3 $3 $19) (21. Qe1 Qb5+ 22. Kg1 Ne2+ $19) 21...
d5 22. Qxc3 (22. Qc5 Qa6+ 23. b5 Nxb5 $19) 22... Rxc3 23. Bxc3 Qc7 {The g3
rook is hanging and so is the bishop on c3. What a powerful game by
Miroshnichenko! One of those games which makes you believe in the power of the
move b5 followed by c6.} 0-1

