1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 O-O 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 b5 $5 {Adorjan
line!} 7. cxb5 c6 8. Bg5 $1 {This is the most challenging move against this
system. The main reason is that White is saying, 'I don't mind if material
equality is established, but I don't want to be passive - I want my bishop to
be active on the g5 square'.} cxb5 9. e3 Bb7 {Black develops without losing
time.} 10. Nf3 (10. f3 {Is also a possible move, but White further postpones
his development.} a6 11. Bd3 Nc6 12. Ne2 Rc8 {Black continues with his natural
development.} 13. Qd2 h6 14. Bh4 Ne4 $1 {This simplifying manoeuvre often
comes in other lines against the Qc2 Nimzo Indian.} 15. Bxd8 Nxd2 16. Kxd2
Rfxd8 {I must agree that Black's chances of winning this position are not too
bright, but he is close to equality. In particular, White hasn't caused him a
lot of problems.} 17. b4 Ne7 18. a4 (18. Rhc1 f5 $11) 18... bxa4 19. Rxa4 Rc6
20. Rha1 Rb6 $11 {Mostly the a6 and b4 pawns will be exchanged and a drawn
endgame will be reached.}) 10... h6 11. Bxf6 $6 {I think this move is very
cooperative. Black will hardly face any problems after this. Better was to
retreat with Bh4, as seen in our next game.} Qxf6 12. Be2 (12. Bxb5 Bxf3) 12...
Rc8 13. Qd3 a6 14. O-O Nc6 {According to my understanding, Black has already
equalised. He has perfect development and also better control on the light
squares on the board. His plans can include Na5-c4 or Ne7-d5.} 15. b4 $2 {
Atalik writes that being annoyed with the easy equality that Black had
achieved, he made this move and immediately began to regret it. The main
reason is that the c4 square has been weakened irreversibly.} (15. Nd2 Na5 (
15... Ne7 16. Rfc1 $11) 16. Rfc1 $11 {Was a much more conservative way to play.
}) 15... Ne7 $1 {The knight begins his odyssey towards the c4 square with
Nd5-b6 or Nf5-d6.} 16. Rfc1 (16. a4 bxa4 17. Rxa4 Nd5 18. Qd2 Nc3 $17) 16...
Nd5 17. Qd2 Nb6 18. Rxc8+ Rxc8 19. Rc1 Qd8 $1 $15 {Black keeps control and has
the much more pleasant position. His bishop works wonderfully and his knight
is able to keep an eye on the weak square. In short, White has his work cut
out to earn a draw.} 20. Ne1 Bd5 21. f3 Rxc1 (21... Nc4) 22. Qxc1 Bc4 23. Bd1 (
23. Bxc4 $5 Nxc4 24. Qc3 Qg5 25. Nc2 $15 {Was a serious option, but Black is
better.}) 23... Qg5 24. f4 Qd5 25. Nf3 Qb7 (25... Bb3 26. Be2 {White will
avoid the exchange of light-squared bishops because, if he does exchange them,
then his queen side pawns will be extremely weak.}) 26. Ne5 {All endings are
bad for White.} (26. Nd2 Bd5 27. Bf3 Bxf3 28. gxf3 Nc4 29. Nxc4 Qc6 $17) 26...
d6 $1 (26... Bd5 27. Qc5) 27. Bf3 Bd5 28. Bxd5 Qxd5 29. Qc7 dxe5 30. Qxb6 exd4
31. exd4 $2 {Having repaired my position by some sensible play, I once again
destroy it!} (31. Qxd4 {Was a better option.} Qb3 {Since the pawn endgame is a
draw, this is forced.} (31... Qxd4 $2 32. exd4 Kf8 33. Kf2 Ke7 34. Ke3 Kd6 35.
Ke4 f5+ 36. Ke3 Kd5 37. Kd3 g5 38. fxg5 hxg5 39. Ke3 (39. g3 g4) 39... f4+ 40.
Kd3 e5 41. dxe5 Kxe5 42. g3 $11) 32. h4 Qxa3 33. Kh2 $17 {Gives Black good
winning chances.}) 31... Qe4 $19 {Now with this terrible bunch of pawns, White
is lost.} (31... Qb3 $5 $19) 32. Qb8+ (32. g3 Qe3+ 33. Kg2 Qxa3 34. Qc5 a5 35.
bxa5 Qxa5 $19) 32... Kh7 33. Qe5 Qb1+ 34. Kf2 Qb2+ 35. Kf1 Qxa3 36. Qc5 a5 $1
37. Qc2+ f5 38. bxa5 b4 $1 $19 0-1

