1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 O-O 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 b5 7. cxb5 c6 8.
Bg5 cxb5 9. e3 Bb7 10. Nf3 h6 11. Bxf6 $6 {As we know from the last game, this
move is too cooperative and gives White few chances to fight for an advantage.}
Qxf6 12. Be2 Rc8 13. Qd3 a6 14. O-O Nc6 {Till here we have been following
Atalik-Csaba. But now White makes a better move than Atalik's b4.} 15. Rac1 Na5
{The knight jumps into an active square, keeping an eye on the weak c4 and b3
squares.} 16. Nd2 Qg5 {Just a probing move.} 17. Bf3 (17. e4 {Loses to a
little tactic: can you spot it?} Rxc1 $1 18. Rxc1 Nc4 $1 {And White will lose
at least a pawn or have a very bad position.} 19. Rc2 Nxd2 20. Rxd2 f5 $1 21.
f3 fxe4 22. fxe4 Qh4 $17) 17... Bxf3 18. Nxf3 Qd5 $1 {The queen occupies an
important central square. Look how all of Black's pieces are working nicely on
the light squares.} 19. b4 Nc4 $15 {Black is now better because of his active
knight.} 20. Nd2 Nxd2 $1 {Sometimes simplification is the best way to increase
the advantage. Now the Black queen penetrates into White's position.} 21. Qxd2
Qb3 $17 22. Rxc8+ Rxc8 23. Ra1 (23. Rc1 Rc4 $1 {And White can hardly move!})
23... Rc2 {Black's active major pieces will seal the deal for him.} 24. Qe1 {
The queen can't move because of the f2 pawn and the rook cannot move due to
the a3 pawn!} Qb2 25. Rb1 Qxa3 26. Ra1 Qb2 27. Rb1 Qa2 28. Ra1 Qb3 29. h3 (29.
Rxa6 Qxb4 $1 $19) 29... Rc6 {Black has gained a pawn and wins the game in a
few more moves.} 30. g3 f5 31. h4 Qd5 32. Qf1 Kf7 33. Qd1 Kg6 34. Qf1 Kf6 35.
Qd1 Qd6 36. Qe1 Rc4 37. Kg2 Ke7 38. Rb1 Qd5+ 39. Kg1 Qf3 40. Ra1 g5 41. h5 Qc6
42. Rb1 Qe4 43. Qd1 f4 44. gxf4 gxf4 45. Rb3 f3 {The way Moradibadia Elshan
played in this game reminds me of Capablanca. He exchanged the pieces without
any worries of a draw. With every exchange, his pieces remaining on the board
grew in power and the last position is a testimony to that. What I
particularly want you to notice is Black's light square play right from the
opening, with moves like b5, Na5, Qd5.} 0-1

