1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 O-O 5. e4 {This move has become popular
recently. It is a very aggressive and captures the centre. Black has no time
to play positional chess now, as he has already castled. So I think the best
reaction is to strike in the centre.} d5 $1 6. e5 {This is the only logical
move that White has.} Ne4 7. Bd3 c5 $1 {Black keeps on hitting White's centre.
In the lines with Qc2, we often see very energetic play by black because he is
trying to profit from the lead in development that he has over White's other
advantages. White has four choices here: 1. Nf3; 2. Nge2; 3. a3; 4. cd5. One
small note would come in handy here. After Nf3 and Nge2, White has the choice
of taking on d4 and both will convert to the same line - which is the game
continuation. But to Nge2, I have suggested one more option for Black - if
ever you want to use it...} 8. Nf3 {Now we have to take on d4, as Nc6 doesn't
work so well because the e5 pawn will be protected by Nf3.} (8. Nge2 Nc6 $5 {
This is played less frequently, but I think it is a very interesting move.} (
8... cxd4 {Of course, we can merely convert to the main line by taking here on
d4, but it doesn't hurt to have an extra choice just in case you want to try
something different some day.}) 9. cxd5 exd5 10. O-O (10. a3 cxd4 $1 11. axb4
Nxb4) 10... cxd4 11. Nxd5 Qxd5 12. Bxe4 Qxe5 13. Bxh7+ Kh8 {Everything was
